Youssif, the burned Iraqi boy, met his favorite superhero at Universal Studios. "It was my favorite thing," the boy said later. He met SpongeBob, Lassie and a 3-year-old orangutan named Archie. The father and mother grinned from ear to ear throughout the day.
NEW: O.J. Simpson will be held without bail after his arrest on robbery charges. NEW: Police say they have no information leading them to believe Simpson was carrying a firearm. Simpson is accused of having directed several other men in an alleged armed robbery. Two firearms that police said were used were recovered early Sunday.
Cpl. Trent D. Thomas will be demoted to the rank of entry-level private. He was found guilty Wednesday of kidnapping and conspiracy to commit several offenses. Thomas was among seven Marines and a Navy medic charged in the death of Hashim Ibrahim Awad.
Francesco Totti has threatened to quit the Italian Players Association. Totti is unhappy with the starting date of the next Serie A season. The Italian Football League voted to start the season on August 26. Italy coach Roberto Donadoni wanted the first round of matches midway through the month.
Roy Lynn Oakley, 67, of Roane County, Tennessee, appeared in federal court in Knoxville. Oakley is a former employee of Bechtel Jacobs, the Department of Energy's prime environmental management contractor. He is accused of stealing restricted nuclear energy-related materials and putting the U.S. at risk.
Nigeria's television survival show suspended after contestant drowns. Anthony Ogadje, 25, and nine other contestants had gone to Shere Hills Lake. "Gulder Ultimate Search" sets a variety of physical challenges for participants. Broadcasting had been due to start on Thursday.
A shortage of donated organs in rich countries is sending foreigners to poorer places. Doctors in Pakistan have been arrested for abducting people, drugging them and stealing kidneys. Donors in South Africa receive $700 for a kidney compared with $30,000 in the U.S.
12-year-old Mohammed Rasoul lost his right leg in an explosion in Falluja, Iraq. His story caught the attention of an American charity, the Global Medical Relief Fund. The charity has arranged for surgery and treatment at the Shriners Children Hospital. Mohammed will arrive in the United States on Thursday.
One-Two-Go jet crashed in bad weather as it landed at Phuket's airport on Sunday. Most of those killed were foreign nationals, and about 36 of the bodies still have yet to be identified. Investigation into what caused the crash continues, but the strong winds and rain are a suspected factor.
